Q: using java Calendar A: <h2>tl;dr</h2>
<p>Make a record class using <code>java.time.LocalDate</code> class, with immutable objects.</p>
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint-override"><code>public Ticket ( String what , String where , LocalDate when ) 
{
    public Ticket with ( final LocalDate differentDate ) 
    {
        if ( this.when.isEqual( differentDate ) ) return this ;
        return new Ticket ( this.what , this.where , differentDate ) ; 
    }

    public Ticket move ( final Period period ) 
    {
        return this.with( this.when.plus( period ) ) ; 
    }
}
</code></pre>
<h2>Details</h2>
<p>The <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/a/2484639/642706">Answer by Bozho</a> and the <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/a/2484674/642706">Answer by Jon Skeet</a> are both correct and smart. Modern Java now offers a better solution.</p>
<h3><em>java.time</em></h3>
<p>The legacy date-time classes such as <code>Date</code> and <code>Calendar</code> are tragically flawed. They were supplanted by the modern <em>java.time</em> classes built into Java 8 and later, as specified in JSR 310.</p>
<h4><code>LocalDate</code></h4>
<p>For a date-only value (year-month-day), use <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/time/LocalDate.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><code>java.time.LocalDate</code></a> class.</p>
<p>The <em>java.time</em> classes use <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immutable_object" rel="nofollow noreferrer">immutable objects</a>. So create fresh instances rather modifying (mutating) the original.</p>
<h4>Records</h4>
<p>If the main purpose of your class is to transparently communicate shallowly-immutable data, make your class a <a href="https://openjdk.org/jeps/395" rel="nofollow noreferrer">record</a>.</p>
<pre><code>public Ticket ( String what , String where , LocalDate when ) {}
</code></pre>
<p>The compiler implicitly creates the constructor and <code>Object</code> overrides for <code>equals</code> , <code>hashCode</code>, and <code>toString</code>. And the compiler implicitly creates accessor “getter” methods for each field.</p>
<pre><code>List &lt; Ticket &gt; tickets =
    List.of(
        new Ticket ( &quot;Concert&quot; , &quot;Stadium&quot; , LocalDate.of( 2026 , 1 , 23 ) ) ,
        new Ticket ( &quot;Reading&quot; , &quot;Library&quot; , LocalDate.of( 2026 , 1 , 23 ) ) ,
        new Ticket ( &quot;Meeting&quot; , &quot;Conference Room&quot; , LocalDate.of( 2026 , 2 , 7 ) ) 
    );
</code></pre>
<h4>Withers</h4>
<p>You want to get a <code>Ticket</code> with a changed date.</p>
<p>Per <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/datetime/overview/naming.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">naming conventions</a>, we add method <code>with</code> to get a new <code>Ticket</code> object having a different date but the same values of the other fields.</p>
<p>Per immutable objects, we create a new <code>Ticket</code> object when changing the date.</p>
<p>FYI, the Java team is working on adding built-in support for these kinds of <a href="https://openjdk.org/jeps/468" rel="nofollow noreferrer">“wither” methods</a>. But for now we write our own (or ask an AI to do the drudgery).</p>
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint-override"><code>public Ticket ( String what , String where , LocalDate when ) 
{
    public Ticket with ( final LocalDate differentDate ) 
    {
        if ( this.when.isEqual( differentDate ) ) return this ;
        return new Ticket ( this.what , this.where , differentDate ) ; 
    }
}
</code></pre>
<h4>Date-time math</h4>
<p>You can perform date-time math by calling the <code>plus</code> &amp; <code>minus</code> methods.</p>
<p>Your code takes a mere <code>int</code> value in its <code>move</code> method. We can do better than that. We can have a parameter of type <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/time/Period.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><code>Period</code></a> for any number of years, months, days.</p>
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint-override"><code>public Ticket ( String what , String where , LocalDate when ) 
{
    public Ticket with ( final LocalDate differentDate ) 
    {
        if ( this.when.isEqual( differentDate ) ) return this ;
        return new Ticket ( this.what , this.where , differentDate ) ; 
    }

    public Ticket move ( final Period period ) 
    {
        return this.with( this.when.plus( period ) ) ; 
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Example usage:</p>
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint-override"><code>Ticket weekLater = someTicket.move( Period.ofDays( 7 ) ) ;
</code></pre>

Q: Run spark program locally with intellij A: <p>I ran into this issue as well, and I also had an old cloudera hadoop reference in my code. (You have to click the 'edited' link in the original poster's link to see his original pom settings).</p>

<p>I could leave that reference in as long as I put this at the <em>top of my dependencies</em> (order matters!).  You should match it against your own hadoop cluster settings.</p>

<pre><code>&lt;dependency&gt;
  &lt;!-- THIS IS REQUIRED FOR LOCAL RUNNING IN INTELLIJ --&gt;
  &lt;!-- IT MUST REMAIN AT TOP OF DEPENDENCY LIST TO 'WIN' AGAINST OLD HADOOP CODE BROUGHT IN--&gt;
  &lt;groupId&gt;org.apache.hadoop&lt;/groupId&gt;
  &lt;artifactId&gt;hadoop-mapreduce-client-core&lt;/artifactId&gt;
  &lt;version&gt;2.6.0-cdh5.12.0&lt;/version&gt;
  &lt;scope&gt;provided&lt;/scope&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;
</code></pre>

<p>Note that in 2018.1 version of Intellij, you can check <em>Include dependiencies with "Provided" Scope</em> which is a simple way to keep your pom scopes clean.</p>

Q: Add image inside search box? A: <p>You can solve it like this:</p>
<p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="false" data-console="true" data-babel="false">
<div class="snippet-code">
<pre class="snippet-code-css lang-css prettyprint-override"><code>@mixin searchbar-font {}

@mixin searchbar-styles {
  border: none;
  outline: none;
  color: $header-bg-color;
  padding: 20px 65px 20px 20px;
  background: transparent;
  flex: 1;
}

@mixin search-bar-input {
  border: none;
  outline: none;
}

.search-input {
  border: none;
  outline: none;
